'''Wanikawa Shrine''' (わにかわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Miki|Q1205980|WD=Q1205980|1=Miki, Kagawa}}, {{ill|lt=Kita District|Q1155929|WD=Q1155929|1=Kita District, Kagawa}}, {{ill|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|Q161454|WD=Q161454|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}. It is one of the {{ill|lt=candidate shrines|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} for Wanikawa Shrine, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} of {{ill|lt=Miki District|Q10866143|WD=Q10866143|1=Miki district}}, {{ill|lt=Sanuki Province|Q929682|WD=Q929682|1=Sanuki Province}}.

In Miki there is also {{ill|lt=Wanigawa Shrine|Q11674320|WD=Q11674320|1=Wanikawa Shrine}}, likewise read “wanikawa jinja,” and that shrine is also a candidate for the same Shikinaisha<ref>Other candidate shrines include {{ill|lt=Hakusan Shrine (Miki)|Q11579589|WD=Q11579589|lt=Hakusan Shrine|1=Hakusan Shrine (Q11579589)}} in Shimotakaoka, Miki, and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hikimiya Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in Inoue, Miki.</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
=== Main deity ===
*{{ill|WD=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime|Q2329261|WD=Q2329261|WD=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}}

=== Associated deities ===
*{{ill|lt=Tamayori-hime (Hyūga mythology)|Q3082751|WD=Q3082751|lt=Tamayori-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)}}
*{{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|lt=Hachiman Ōkami|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
*{{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|WD=Q232803|lt=Okinagatarashihime-no-Mikoto|1=Empress Jingū}}

=== Origin ===
The founding period is unknown. According to shrine tradition, Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto rode a {{ill|lt=shark|Q7372|WD=Q7372|lt=wani|1=Shark}} upstream and landed here. That river is called Wani River ({{ill|lt=Kamobe River|Q11675608|WD=Q11675608|1=Kabe River}}).

There are records of several {{ill|lt=sengū (shrine relocations)|Q2271023|WD=Q2271023|1=Sengū}} from the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|lt=Heian|1=Heian period}} through the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. There are four candidate shrines for the Shikinaisha Wanikawa Shrine, and this is presumed to reflect those many relocations.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), it became a {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Other ===
*The river Toyotama-hime-no-Mikoto ascended on a wani later came to be called Wani River, said to be today’s {{ill|lt=Kamobe River|Q11675608|WD=Q11675608|1=Kabe River}}<ref>The other candidate shrines for Wanikawa Shikinaisha, Wanigawa and Hakusan Shrines, identify Wani River with {{ill|lt=Shinkawa (Kagawa)|Q11502062|WD=Q11502062|lt=Shinkawa|1=Shinkawa River}}.</ref>

===Access===
*20 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Kumonmyō Station|Q11392051|WD=Q11392051|1=Kumonmyō Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagao Line|Q5364831|WD=Q5364831|1=Kotoden Nagao Line}} of {{ill|lt=Takamatsu-Kotohira Electric Railroad|Q566998|WD=Q566998|1=Takamatsu-Kotohira Electric Railroad}}.

